node.text:
Yesterday I shared a story from @willtrubridge about why no one should practice Wim Hoff techniques with breath holds. So many people wrote back asking, 'why not?' So I thought I'd explain in a post.

It's best to breathe slowly and shallow before we hold our breath. To breathe as if we were trying to fall asleep. When we breathe fast or heavily (hyperventilate) we do not alter the amount of oxygen in our body we only decrease our carbon dioxide levels (it is a physical impossibility to increase the amount of oxygen in our body by breathing atmospheric air.) 

Our body needs carbon dioxide to hold its breath effectively. When we hyperventilate we not only postpone the urge to breathe. We decrease the period of time we can hold our breath for before we black out.

As far as I'm aware most Wim Hoff techniques involve some fairly aggressive hyperventilation.  So when people use these techniques with breath holds they feel great during the breath hold and then they black out very early!

I have nothing against the ice man but his techniques should not be used for breath holds 😊 if you want more info into the physiology look up 'the bohr effect' and 'the oxygen dissasociation curve' #freediving #wimhoff #blackout 

Freediver in this shot is @sallywagon

node.text:
I've been getting a lot of questions about why I'm not competing at Vertical Blue this year and the answer is simple...we're still not allowed to leave Australia 😂 It's been amazing watching everyone doing monster dives though! 

We have been having a magical time at the farm. We're getting ready for baby Ari, planting birthday trees and landscaping. With the help of @drawn_2water we have even built a tiny house! 

I feel like this will be a time in our lives that we always look back on. When we lived in a little house we built on the farm and the kids were young 😊 #farmlife #australia #paradise
